  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2201036498" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2201036498" />
    <a title="Cynnamon" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/73483095-cynnamon"><img alt="Cynnamon" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1541975560p2/73483095.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2201036498?book_show_action=true">Jul 02, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Cynnamon" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Cynnamon" href="/user/show/73483095-cynnamon">Cynnamon</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781481425445" href="/book/show/22540210-the-monstrumologist">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/73483095-cynnamon?shelf=kat-horror">kat-horror</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/73483095-cynnamon?shelf=kat-gothic">kat-gothic</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2201036498" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10717972932763499086"><b>Not the run-of-the-mill monster hunter story</b><br/><br/>I started into this book with completely wrong expectations.<br/>I expected an action-driven, thrilling monster hunter story that would make my blood freeze.<br/><br/>What I got was fictious diaries from the 19th century. The author of the diaries, Will Henry, was a stunningly old man who had recently died in a nursing home. He had been writing down his memories beginning from his childhood in 1888, but obviously he started the writing only later as a grown man.<br/><br/>So wh</span>
  <span id="freeText10717972932763499086" style="display:none"><b>Not the run-of-the-mill monster hunter story</b><br /><br />I started into this book with completely wrong expectations.<br />I expected an action-driven, thrilling monster hunter story that would make my blood freeze.<br /><br />What I got was fictious diaries from the 19th century. The author of the diaries, Will Henry, was a stunningly old man who had recently died in a nursing home. He had been writing down his memories beginning from his childhood in 1888, but obviously he started the writing only later as a grown man.<br /><br />So what we have here is a report from the perspective of a 12-year old who lives with and works for an obscure scientist in the field of monstrumology.<br /><br />The way the story is told is very old-fashioned, in wording and style, and therefore reads rather unhurried and without any focus on thrill or action, more or less like a slow historical novel. The authoring boy was often too dumbstruck by inexplicable events or to frightened to show a high level of spirited narration style.<br /><br />So in the beginning the book did not suck me in in any ways, so that I started being a little bit bored, but I didn’t lose interest completely.<br /><br />In the second half, the book picked up pace, though. I also became aware that I had completely neglected other aspects of the work.<br /><br />I realized that the author discussed a lot of really interesting philosophical questions, like guilt, responsibility and what it means to be human.<br /><br />Also the relationship between Will Henry and his monster hunter boss is extremely interesting. It seems to develop in the course of the series and I started being really interested in what will happen to the two of them and to find out what kind of person the monstrumologist really is.<br /><br />The book has some framing story line of a contemporary writer who reads the diaries and starts researching the background to find out, if there are any facts behind the story in the notebook. I don’t know if Rick Yancey will follow up on this, but this could render some interestingly unexpected results also.<br /><br />So the book did not meet my expectations (which were preconceived and obviously wrong), but it could spike my interest on other levels and I will definitely like to follow up with the next book in the series.<br /><br />3.5 stars, upgraded.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="10717972932763499086" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


